<subSubSection id="9983A9D91B0DFFC1FF44FF2FFBCEFB66" pageId="19" pageNumber="530" type="description">
<paragraph id="D126FA521B0DFFC1FF44FF2FFBCEFB66" blockId="19.[205,1413,822,1565]" pageId="19" pageNumber="530">
<emphasis id="E3ED26401B0DFFC1FF44FF2FFE57FCA3" bold="true" box="[208,455,862,895]" pageId="19" pageNumber="530">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 166-174 mm, tail 73-80 mm, hindfoot (with claw) 34-8— 37 mm; weight 146-187 g, all measurements from three specimens. The Paraguayan Tuco-tuco is medium-sized. It has prominent, pale semi-collar, passing obliquely from below ears, around back of head, reaching base of neck. Cheeks are lighter; face lacks any blackish color. Venter is creamy gray, showing no inguinal or axillary white spots. Tail is slightly bicolored. Skull is gracile. Zygomatic arches have widths across them greater than across external auditory tubes; rim of zygomatic arch lacks foramen. Another notable feature shared with species in north-eastern Argentina and Uruguay is superior placement of auditory meatus in relation to cheekteeth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
